AVIAN INFLUENZA - BELGIUM EX THAILAND: SMUGGLED BIRDS
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Sun 24 Oct 2004
From: Henry Niman <henry_niman@recombinomics.com>
Source: CNN.com, Associated Press Report, Sun 24 Oct 2004 [edited]
<http://www.cnn.com/2004/WORLD/europe/10/24/bird.flu.smuggler.ap/index.html>

Belgium: avian influenza virus-infected eagles smuggled into Brussels by air
-----------------------------------------------
A Thai man, who tried to smuggle 2 small eagles infected with avian
influenza virus into Belgium, was undergoing medical tests on Sun 24 Oct
2004, but appeared to be in good health, officials said. Authorities
detained the man after a manhunt and took him to a hospital in the northern
port city of Antwerp. "It's precautionary ... he hasn't complained of any
symptoms," Rene Snacken of the Public Health Institute told RTBF television.
The man, whose name was not released, had been detained briefly on Monday
[18 Oct 2004], after authorities discovered the birds hidden in plastic
tubes in his hand luggage, which he had carried on flights from Bangkok via
Vienna. The birds were destroyed, but the man was released. Health
authorities then launched a manhunt, appealing to him to report to police
and saying he was at risk of contracting the virus from his contact with
the birds. It was not immediately clear whether he had handed himself in or
was found by police on Sunday [24 Oct 2004].
Health authorities stressed there was little chance he could have passed
the disease to other people. European and Belgian authorities, however,
urged passengers on the same flight as the birds to contact doctors if they
developed flu symptoms in the next 7 days. The man and his birds flew on
EVA Airways flight BR0061 from Bangkok to Vienna, arriving in the Austrian
capital on 18 Oct 2004, then connected with Austrian Airlines flight OS351
to Brussels. "Although the risk of transmission from animals to humans is
limited, it cannot be excluded, since the birds traveled in the passenger
cabin," an EU statement said. In Vienna, Austrian Airlines spokesman
Johannes Davoras told the Austrian Press Agency that all 128 people on the
Brussels-bound flight would be contacted and asked to undergo a medical
examination.
The crested hawk eagles were destroyed immediately at the quarantined
holding zone of Brussels International Airport. Post-mortem tests showed
they were infected. Thailand is a center of a bird flu outbreak that has
devastated poultry farms in Asia. The disease has killed more than 30
people in Thailand and Viet Nam, and forced the culling of over 100 million
birds across much of Asia.
Belgium and other European Union nations have banned imports of live birds
and bird products from several Asian nations. Smuggling of birds of prey is
common, with collectors willing to pay thousands of euros for live birds,
officials said. Europe had its own outbreak of bird flu last year [2003],
which resulted in the culling of 30 million chickens and other birds in the
Netherlands, Belgium, and Germany.
The EU played down any risk from this week's smuggled eagles. "The birds
never left the quarantine installations on Brussels airport and did not
pose any threat to the European poultry flock," the EU statement said.
Customs and health officials in contact with the birds at Brussels airport
have been given medical checks and anti-viral medicines. In Bangkok, the
Thai Public Health Ministry said the case should not cause great concern
since only poultry, such as chickens, and not wild birds have been known to
transmit bird flu directly to humans. The ministry said it believed the
birds originated from outside Thailand.
--
Henry Niman
<henry_niman@recombinomics.com>
