Date: Mon 25 Oct 2004
From: Henry Niman <henry_niman@recombinomics.com>
Source: Nationmultimedia.com, Mon 25 Oct 2004 [edited]
<http://www.nationmultimedia.com/2004/10/26/headlines/index.php?news=headlines_15180182.html>

Veterinarian in contact with infected eagles shows symptoms of bird flu
-----------------------------------------------
A Thai man, who smuggled infected birds from Bangkok, appears to be free of
disease, but a veterinarian, who put down 2 small eagles smuggled from
Thailand shortly after they were discovered at Brussels airport last week,
is sick in the hospital with symptoms of avian influenza, Belgian officials
revealed late yesterday [Sun 24 Oct 2004].
A wildlife campaigner in Thailand, who spoke to the Belgian authorities
last night [24 Oct 2004], said the news was bad. "It means people here will
now [attempt to destroy] birds of prey," said the wildlife expert, who
preferred not to be named.
The Thai man who tried to smuggle the birds into Belgium was undergoing
medical checks last night [24 Oct 2004], but appeared to be in good health,
local officials said. Authorities feared that the man, who they did not
name, may also have the deadly disease. Freed on bail after being caught
with the eagles at Brussels International Airport, the man was detained
again on Sun 24 Oct 2004 and taken to a hospital in the northern port city
of Antwerp. "It's precautionary ... he hasn't complained of any symptoms,"
Rene Snacken of the Public Health Institute told RTBF television.
Customs authorities discovered the birds hidden in plastic tubes in the
man's hand luggage, which he had carried on flights from Bangkok via
Vienna. Health authorities then launched a manhunt, appealing for the
smuggler to report to police, saying he was at risk of contracting the
virus from his contact with the birds. It was not immediately clear whether
he had handed himself in or was found by police. Doctors stressed there was
little chance he could have passed the disease to other people. European
and Belgian authorities, however, urged passengers on the same flight as
the birds to contact doctors if they develop flu symptoms in the next 7 days.
[The remainder of this report duplicates the last part of the preceding
report and has been omitted. - Mod.CP]
