[3]
Date: Mon 25 Oct 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: EU press release IP/04/1295, 24 Oct 2004 [edited]
<http://europa.eu.int/comm/food/library/press003_en.pdf>

Avian flu: illegal imports of birds of prey from Asia, possible exposure of
flight passengers
-----------------------------------------------
After the discovery of avian flu H5N1 in 2 illegally imported birds of prey
from Thailand, the Belgian authorities have requested the European
Commission to assist them in their search for flight passengers of
different nationalities who might have been exposed to the flu virus.
Passengers who traveled on 17/18 Oct 2004 from Bangkok to Vienna with EVA
Airways, flight number BR 0061 (arriving in Vienna on 18 Oct 2004 at 5:30),
and passengers who traveled on 18 Oct 2004 from Vienna to Brussels with
Austrian Airlines, flight number OS351 (arriving at 8:50), are advised to
see their doctor if they have any flu-type symptoms (nausea, fever, cold).
Although the risk of transmission from the animals to humans is limited, it
cannot be excluded, since the birds traveled in the passenger cabin in hand
luggage. The European Commission supports the efforts of the Belgian
authorities to identify the passengers in order to limit any risks for
those exposed, but, also, to limit any possible introduction of the avian
flu virus into Europe.
The birds were discovered by the customs authority in Brussels airport on
Mon 18 Oct 2004. The birds never left the quarantine installations on
Brussels airport and did not pose any threat to the European poultry flock.
Avian flu has not been diagnosed anywhere in Europe since the outbreak in Asia.
The test results confirming avian flu in the illegal imports were available
this weekend [23-24 Oct 2004]. After a scientific risk assessment, the
Belgian authorities decided to search for the passengers. Although
passenger lists are available for the 2 flights concerned, address details
of the passengers are not known. All precautions have to be taken to avoid
the importation of the avian flu virus into Europe.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Illegal trade in animals is known to play a role in the international
spread of infectious animal diseases. For instance, smuggled fighting cocks
from Thailand were found by the Malaysians to be the mode of the H5N1 avian
influenza virus introduction in August 2004.
In January 2004, avian influenza virus subtype H5N1 was detected in Hong
Kong in the carcass of a peregrine falcon, which had been found dead. - Mod.AS]
